 actions, writings, contexts, and conflicts of specific groups of women. The topics include the experience of first-generation university students, public debates about female homosexuality, and the stories of three civil servants whose careers were ruined by workplace accusations of homosexuality. The book concludes with a debate between the women who joined the 1920s homosexual movement on the meanings of their new identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aLesbianism -- Germany -- History -- 19th century. 0aLesbianism -- Germany -- History -- 20th century. 0aLesbianismzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aLesbianismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aLesbians -- Germany -- History -- 19th century. 0aLesbians -- Germany -- History -- 20th century. 0aLesbianszGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aLesbianszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 4aArea Studies : German Studies. 4aCultural Studies : German Culture. 4aGender and Sexuality : Lesbian / Gay Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aHistory : European History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438452234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438452234/original  a978-3-11-149015-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles